00:01:34.800 --> 00:01:36.360
What is positive psychology?

00:01:36.360 --> 00:01:39.690
Basically, about 20
years ago, a researcher

00:01:39.690 --> 00:01:42.780
from University of
Pennsylvania, Marty Seligman,

00:01:42.780 --> 00:01:47.440
realized that when we dealt
with research in psychology,

00:01:47.440 --> 00:01:52.140
it always had to do with
mental health, of course,

00:01:52.140 --> 00:01:54.330
but with mental diseases.

00:01:54.330 --> 00:01:58.050
And basically, he was elected
at the head of the Psychology

00:01:58.050 --> 00:02:01.020
Institute of the United States,
which basically brings together

00:02:01.020 --> 00:02:02.100
researchers.

00:02:02.100 --> 00:02:04.680
And Seligman said,
why don't we try

00:02:04.680 --> 00:02:08.699
and see if we could think
research differently to come up

00:02:08.699 --> 00:02:12.150
with a preventive psychology?

00:02:12.150 --> 00:02:14.430
Because we all know
that, in health matters,

00:02:14.430 --> 00:02:16.740
there are things that we
can do more of or less

00:02:16.740 --> 00:02:20.590
of that will enable us to
live longer in better health.

00:02:20.590 --> 00:02:24.420
But on a mental level,
are there things

00:02:24.420 --> 00:02:28.990
that we can do more of or
less of that will enable us--

00:02:28.990 --> 00:02:30.840
so what can it enable us to do?

00:02:30.840 --> 00:02:35.550
Not so much avoid the hardships
of life, because the hardships

00:02:35.550 --> 00:02:36.900
will be coming our way.

00:02:36.900 --> 00:02:39.220
Maybe they have
already come your way.

00:02:39.220 --> 00:02:42.310
But the good news is, they
are heading towards us.

00:02:42.310 --> 00:02:44.700
So since they are
heading towards us,

00:02:44.700 --> 00:02:49.500
to know how to get
back on our feet

00:02:49.500 --> 00:02:54.060
in order to feel more power
to be able to get back

00:02:54.060 --> 00:02:57.750
in our daily lives after
miserable things happen to us.

00:02:57.750 --> 00:03:01.590
That's when he decides to
create a new area of research.

00:03:01.590 --> 00:03:04.170
Positive psychology is
actually brings together

00:03:04.170 --> 00:03:06.690
researchers from
different psychology labs

00:03:06.690 --> 00:03:08.310
who work on three things--

00:03:08.310 --> 00:03:13.500
behaviors, personalities,
and organizations that work.

00:03:13.500 --> 00:03:15.379
It's also called the
science of happiness.

00:03:15.379 --> 00:03:17.170
Have you heard of the
science of happiness?

00:03:17.170 --> 00:03:17.751
OK.

00:03:17.751 --> 00:03:18.250
Wonderful.

00:03:18.250 --> 00:03:20.760
So this is what
positive psychology is.

00:03:20.760 --> 00:03:23.070
So my job-- my day job--

00:03:23.070 --> 00:03:26.100
I have a few jobs,
but my day job

00:03:26.100 --> 00:03:29.730
is to actually be a
happiness teacher.

00:03:29.730 --> 00:03:32.520
So what I do is look
at the research,

00:03:32.520 --> 00:03:36.420
try everything before
I get anywhere to talk

00:03:36.420 --> 00:03:37.740
or write about it.

00:03:37.740 --> 00:03:40.350
And thanks for the author thing.

00:03:40.350 --> 00:03:42.030
I have published
books, so maybe I

00:03:42.030 --> 00:03:44.040
am the first author that
you are seeing here.

00:03:44.040 --> 00:03:45.490
I don't know, maybe.

00:03:45.490 --> 00:03:48.810
Anyway, before I write anything,
before I talk about anything,

00:03:48.810 --> 00:03:50.250
I actually try it out.

00:03:50.250 --> 00:03:52.770
And I guess that's how
I'm able to come, then,

00:03:52.770 --> 00:03:55.500
and tell you what
we can possibly do.

00:03:55.500 --> 00:03:57.840
Positive psychology
is information.

00:03:57.840 --> 00:03:59.520
It's not therapy.

00:03:59.520 --> 00:04:02.730
Once you know that there
are certain behaviors that

00:04:02.730 --> 00:04:05.400
can lead us to feel
this way or that,

00:04:05.400 --> 00:04:08.370
then you are completely
free to try it out.

00:04:08.370 --> 00:04:10.420
So since this is
all about happiness,

00:04:10.420 --> 00:04:11.880
let's start with happiness.

00:04:11.880 --> 00:04:13.590
What is happiness?

00:04:13.590 --> 00:04:15.900
Basically, maybe I'll
begin with what it is not.

00:04:15.900 --> 00:04:21.269
Happiness is not the
opposite of unhappiness.

00:04:21.269 --> 00:04:26.010
If you look at your lives,
whatever day goes by,

00:04:26.010 --> 00:04:27.900
whatever month or
year goes by, you

00:04:27.900 --> 00:04:30.720
will be swinging from
one state to the next.

00:04:30.720 --> 00:04:32.250
Sometimes, you feel great.

00:04:32.250 --> 00:04:34.140
Sometimes, you feel awful.

00:04:34.140 --> 00:04:37.830
And maybe the day so far
has gone perfectly well.

00:04:37.830 --> 00:04:43.500
None of us here is protected
from receiving a terrible text

00:04:43.500 --> 00:04:46.300
message where your
world goes upside down.

00:04:46.300 --> 00:04:47.320
None of us.

00:04:47.320 --> 00:04:53.190
But on the other hand, we can
wake up feeling really grumpy,

00:04:53.190 --> 00:04:58.020
and none of us is
protected from a [FRENCH]..

00:04:58.020 --> 00:04:59.550
You know what [FRENCH] is.

00:04:59.550 --> 00:05:01.590
Love at first sight.

00:05:01.590 --> 00:05:03.992
We have no idea what's
going to happen.

00:05:03.992 --> 00:05:05.700
The only thing that
we have to understand

00:05:05.700 --> 00:05:09.690
is that we will be swinging
from one state to the other.

00:05:09.690 --> 00:05:13.770
And the opposite of
happiness is apathy.

00:05:13.770 --> 00:05:16.530
Apathy is when we are
stuck in the middle,

00:05:16.530 --> 00:05:18.100
and we just don't
know where to go.

00:05:18.100 --> 00:05:21.690
And the clinical version of
apathy is called depression.

00:05:21.690 --> 00:05:25.500
And in that particular matter,
we need regular psychology

00:05:25.500 --> 00:05:26.760
to cure us.

00:05:26.760 --> 00:05:29.340
But when we're dealing
with flourishing,

00:05:29.340 --> 00:05:32.400
when we're dealing with, how do
we enjoy the projects that we

00:05:32.400 --> 00:05:32.910
work on?

00:05:32.910 --> 00:05:36.390
How do we enjoy the
relationships that we are in?

00:05:36.390 --> 00:05:40.350
How do we dilate inside of
our little envelope here?

00:05:40.350 --> 00:05:42.210
This is a pretty
small space that we

00:05:42.210 --> 00:05:44.430
each use on this planet.

00:05:44.430 --> 00:05:46.590
Within that little
space, how can we

00:05:46.590 --> 00:05:50.000
use up most of the space
that is ours, actually?

00:05:50.000 --> 00:05:52.950
And that is what positive
psychology is about.

00:05:52.950 --> 00:05:56.690
Let's expand inside who we are.

00:05:56.690 --> 00:05:58.690
So I have a question for you.

00:05:58.690 --> 00:06:03.730
Where does our ability
to be happy come from?

00:06:03.730 --> 00:06:05.560
I'll be a little more specific.

00:06:05.560 --> 00:06:10.750
Who among you believes that our
ability to be happy is genetic?

00:06:10.750 --> 00:06:12.790
That it is pre-programmed.

00:06:12.790 --> 00:06:14.860
Who thinks it is?

00:06:14.860 --> 00:06:17.630
OK, who thinks it's not?

00:06:17.630 --> 00:06:18.820
All right.

00:06:18.820 --> 00:06:20.112
And who doesn't know?

00:06:20.112 --> 00:06:21.050
AUDIENCE: [CHUCKLING]

00:06:21.050 --> 00:06:22.300
FLORENCE SERVAN-SCHREIBER: OK.

00:06:22.300 --> 00:06:26.112
So this is one of the first
things that regular psychology,

00:06:26.112 --> 00:06:27.820
one of the first
questions that they ask.

00:06:27.820 --> 00:06:30.530
Where does our ability
to be happy come from?

00:06:30.530 --> 00:06:31.570
Is it genetic?

00:06:31.570 --> 00:06:34.940
So the first thing they have
to do is scratch their head.

00:06:34.940 --> 00:06:37.840
How can we find that out?

00:06:37.840 --> 00:06:40.520
And they realize there's
only one way to go.

00:06:40.520 --> 00:06:44.190
They are going to have
to find identical twins.

00:06:44.190 --> 00:06:46.120
And identical
twins are basically

00:06:46.120 --> 00:06:49.090
one egg that has been
separated in two pieces.

00:06:49.090 --> 00:06:51.130
So it's the same genetic code.

00:06:51.130 --> 00:06:55.660
But we need these twins to
have been separated at birth,

00:06:55.660 --> 00:06:58.210
adopted in different families.

00:06:58.210 --> 00:07:00.850
And we prefer them to be
older than 40 years old,

00:07:00.850 --> 00:07:03.190
so things have happened to them.

00:07:03.190 --> 00:07:05.170
And these twins come in.

00:07:05.170 --> 00:07:10.850
And the question is, now, to
measure their happiness level.

00:07:10.850 --> 00:07:14.640
So how does one measure
a happiness level?

00:07:14.640 --> 00:07:18.230
Basically, there's no software.

00:07:18.230 --> 00:07:20.830
There's no blood test.

00:07:20.830 --> 00:07:24.190
No saliva tests that can
tell us if you're happy.

00:07:24.190 --> 00:07:28.930
The only way to measure
happiness is self-declarative--

00:07:28.930 --> 00:07:32.050
knowing that you are the only
person to know how you feel.

00:07:32.050 --> 00:07:34.240
So we ask you a
series of questions.

00:07:34.240 --> 00:07:38.060
And you always have to answer
on a scale from 1 to 10.

00:07:38.060 --> 00:07:39.820
So for example,
you can be asked,

00:07:39.820 --> 00:07:43.000
how do you feel about
your current projects?

00:07:43.000 --> 00:07:45.340
Or you can be asked,
how do you feel

00:07:45.340 --> 00:07:47.710
when you look at your peers?

00:07:47.710 --> 00:07:51.730
Or, how do you feel about
your childhood dreams?

00:07:51.730 --> 00:07:53.590
We can also go through emotions.

00:07:53.590 --> 00:07:55.870
How much joy do
you feel right now?

00:07:55.870 --> 00:07:57.130
How much anger?

00:07:57.130 --> 00:07:58.270
How much fear?

00:07:58.270 --> 00:07:59.590
And so forth.

00:07:59.590 --> 00:08:02.620
We sum it all up, and
we have an average.

00:08:02.620 --> 00:08:04.570
That's your happiness score.

00:08:04.570 --> 00:08:08.020
So the twins have very
different lifestyles.

00:08:08.020 --> 00:08:10.030
They are asked all
these questions.

00:08:10.030 --> 00:08:14.980
However, they come
up 90% of them

00:08:14.980 --> 00:08:21.610
declare the exact same level
of happiness as their twin.

00:08:21.610 --> 00:08:23.230
So the researchers
are very happy.

00:08:23.230 --> 00:08:25.660
And they publish, and they
say, OK, ladies and gentlemen,

00:08:25.660 --> 00:08:27.729
happiness is just like height.

00:08:27.729 --> 00:08:28.270
It's genetic.

00:08:31.230 --> 00:08:32.562
The talk is over.

00:08:32.562 --> 00:08:33.461
AUDIENCE: [CHUCKLING]

00:08:33.461 --> 00:08:34.919
FLORENCE
SERVAN-SCHREIBER: OK, this

00:08:34.919 --> 00:08:37.500
is before positive
psychology comes in.

00:08:37.500 --> 00:08:39.240
So we lived with
that for a while.

00:08:39.240 --> 00:08:40.860
And then these new
scientists come

00:08:40.860 --> 00:08:43.710
in with a slightly
different approach

00:08:43.710 --> 00:08:44.940
when it comes to happiness.

00:08:44.940 --> 00:08:48.860
Basically, what they have
figured out is the following.

00:08:48.860 --> 00:08:53.650
The question conditions
the response.

00:08:53.650 --> 00:08:56.490
Which means that,
in if our lives,

00:08:56.490 --> 00:08:58.950
we look for what's
wrong, we will

00:08:58.950 --> 00:09:01.390
find what's wrong right away.

00:09:01.390 --> 00:09:04.320
But if we start looking
for what is right,

00:09:04.320 --> 00:09:06.330
then we will start
looking what is right,

00:09:06.330 --> 00:09:07.830
and what is going
well in our lives.

00:09:07.830 --> 00:09:10.470
So what they see are
the same results,

00:09:10.470 --> 00:09:12.480
but they read them upside down.

00:09:12.480 --> 00:09:15.240
And what they are
interested in are the 10%

00:09:15.240 --> 00:09:19.540
of twins who have the exact same
genetic code as somebody else.

00:09:19.540 --> 00:09:22.980
However, they are
happier or unhappier.

00:09:22.980 --> 00:09:24.850
How is it possible?

00:09:24.850 --> 00:09:28.590
So a woman named Sonja
Lyubomirsky works out

00:09:28.590 --> 00:09:30.780
of UC Davis in California.

00:09:30.780 --> 00:09:34.380
And in her lab, the
only question she asks

00:09:34.380 --> 00:09:36.540
is, where does
happiness comes from?

00:09:36.540 --> 00:09:40.830
She has met people who have
experienced all our wildest

00:09:40.830 --> 00:09:42.240
dreams.

00:09:42.240 --> 00:09:44.220
Winning at the lottery.

00:09:44.220 --> 00:09:46.715
Getting an entire
makeover physically.

00:09:46.715 --> 00:09:48.840
That type of crazy things
that we always think that

00:09:48.840 --> 00:09:50.131
could possibly make us happier.

00:09:50.131 --> 00:09:52.350
Anyway, she went through
a bunch, a bunch, a bunch

00:09:52.350 --> 00:09:53.790
of situations and people.

00:09:53.790 --> 00:09:56.660
And basically, she was
able to figure it out.

00:09:56.660 --> 00:10:02.340
50% of our ability to
experience happiness

00:10:02.340 --> 00:10:05.010
is actually pre-determined.

00:10:05.010 --> 00:10:08.600
It comes from one of our
genes called the 5-HTT.

00:10:08.600 --> 00:10:12.420
5-HTT swims up there
somewhere and is

00:10:12.420 --> 00:10:18.150
responsible for manufacturing
all the neurotransmitters that

00:10:18.150 --> 00:10:19.770
run up in our brains.

00:10:19.770 --> 00:10:25.170
Dopamine, endorphins,
serotonin, oxytocin.

00:10:25.170 --> 00:10:26.520
You know all these words?

00:10:26.520 --> 00:10:29.970
Lots of "-in" words that are
basically all the substances

00:10:29.970 --> 00:10:33.150
that our brain will actually
manufacture when we feel great.

00:10:33.150 --> 00:10:36.330
And when we feel great,
it manufactures even more.

00:10:36.330 --> 00:10:42.360
So the longer the 5-HTT, the
more of these neurotransmitters

00:10:42.360 --> 00:10:45.150
our brain is able
to manufacture.

00:10:45.150 --> 00:10:48.310
The shorter it is, the
drier it is up there.

00:10:48.310 --> 00:10:52.380
So this is why there
are different types

00:10:52.380 --> 00:10:54.030
of personalities.

00:10:54.030 --> 00:10:58.140
And we all have people around
us for whom everything is fun.

00:10:58.140 --> 00:10:59.580
Everything is cool.

00:10:59.580 --> 00:11:03.030
Basically, it's probable that
they have a very long 5-HTT.

00:11:03.030 --> 00:11:05.470
And then for the rest of us,
maybe it's a bit shorter,

00:11:05.470 --> 00:11:08.280
and we don't really experience
things the same way.

00:11:08.280 --> 00:11:09.300
But you know something?

00:11:09.300 --> 00:11:11.190
It's exactly like height.

00:11:11.190 --> 00:11:12.390
It is a lottery.

00:11:12.390 --> 00:11:15.150
But for example, I belong to--

00:11:15.150 --> 00:11:17.940
let's say, I'm a short person.

00:11:17.940 --> 00:11:21.060
Well, I can tell the tall people
that, even at this altitude,

00:11:21.060 --> 00:11:22.620
life is fine.

00:11:22.620 --> 00:11:23.130
We are fine.

00:11:23.130 --> 00:11:26.396
We will get used to
whatever our conditions are.

00:11:26.396 --> 00:11:28.020
And that's the good
thing about humans.

00:11:28.020 --> 00:11:29.940
We're great chameleons.

00:11:29.940 --> 00:11:32.130
So that's half of it--

00:11:32.130 --> 00:11:33.420
of our ability to be happy.

00:11:33.420 --> 00:11:36.610
Now, what else do
we need to be happy?

