FLORENCE
SERVAN-SCHREIBER: Comfort.

00:12:07.080 --> 00:12:08.880
Little money, anybody?

00:12:08.880 --> 00:12:10.600
Nah.

00:12:10.600 --> 00:12:11.700
Really not.

00:12:11.700 --> 00:12:13.470
Sunshine?

00:12:13.470 --> 00:12:14.920
Just the regular stuff.

00:12:14.920 --> 00:12:17.790
There's a lot of regular stuff
that actually makes us happy.

00:12:17.790 --> 00:12:19.620
So if we talk about
regular stuff,

00:12:19.620 --> 00:12:24.810
such as sunshine, comfort,
for example, even health.

00:12:24.810 --> 00:12:25.980
The weather.

00:12:25.980 --> 00:12:28.860
Everybody religiously
looks at the weather.

00:12:28.860 --> 00:12:30.960
It's usually 53% accurate.

00:12:30.960 --> 00:12:31.990
Not much more.

00:12:31.990 --> 00:12:34.560
However, we still look at the
weather as an anticipation

00:12:34.560 --> 00:12:36.300
to our happiness.

00:12:36.300 --> 00:12:40.200
All those things
are circumstances.

00:12:40.200 --> 00:12:43.530
And the outside
circumstances-- even our health

00:12:43.530 --> 00:12:46.080
is a circumstance, actually.

00:12:46.080 --> 00:12:53.100
The circumstances count
for 10% of our happiness.

00:12:53.100 --> 00:12:56.200
But the thing is,
we all have a list--

00:12:56.200 --> 00:12:59.730
it's not even one arm
long, it's two arms long--

00:12:59.730 --> 00:13:06.000
of things that we would like to
change, or meet, or eradicate,

00:13:06.000 --> 00:13:07.320
if it was legal.

00:13:07.320 --> 00:13:10.200
Things where we
think, yes, if I could

00:13:10.200 --> 00:13:12.870
change my life, if
things were different,

00:13:12.870 --> 00:13:15.030
then I would be happier.

00:13:15.030 --> 00:13:17.460
Maybe 10% happier.

00:13:17.460 --> 00:13:19.290
But then of course,
we do sometimes

00:13:19.290 --> 00:13:22.110
need to act on our
circumstances, and we can.

00:13:22.110 --> 00:13:26.160
But what we cannot expect is
that changing the circumstances

00:13:26.160 --> 00:13:28.770
will change everything
that happens.

00:13:28.770 --> 00:13:32.060
So 50% is pre-programmed.

00:13:32.060 --> 00:13:34.470
10% comes from the outside.

00:13:34.470 --> 00:13:35.662
How much is left?

00:13:35.662 --> 00:13:36.426
AUDIENCE: 40%.

00:13:36.426 --> 00:13:37.690
FLORENCE SERVAN-SCHREIBER:
40%, yes.

00:13:37.690 --> 00:13:38.565
You people can count.

00:13:38.565 --> 00:13:39.960
Great.

00:13:39.960 --> 00:13:44.550
So what do these
last 40% rely on?

00:13:44.550 --> 00:13:52.360
They rely on our interpretation
of what happens in our lives.

00:13:52.360 --> 00:13:55.830
And it has been determined
that the happiest people, when

00:13:55.830 --> 00:14:00.480
something does not go the way
they had planned it, what they

00:14:00.480 --> 00:14:05.700
will do is that, rather than
considering it as a setback,

00:14:05.700 --> 00:14:08.910
they will actually feel that
they're already moving forward

00:14:08.910 --> 00:14:11.500
in a different direction.

00:14:11.500 --> 00:14:14.340
Meaning, when
something happens to us

00:14:14.340 --> 00:14:17.550
that upsets us that we did
not plan, we do not want,

00:14:17.550 --> 00:14:19.470
we will be frustrated.

00:14:19.470 --> 00:14:20.940
We will be angry.

00:14:20.940 --> 00:14:21.950
We will be pissed off.

00:14:21.950 --> 00:14:22.970
We may even cry.

00:14:22.970 --> 00:14:25.470
It's called being human.

00:14:25.470 --> 00:14:28.670
But pretty quickly, these
people will say, OK.

00:14:28.670 --> 00:14:30.990
I had planned to go
this way, I'm actually

00:14:30.990 --> 00:14:32.250
going to have to go this way.

00:14:32.250 --> 00:14:36.300
And they get back on their feet,
and they start moving again.

00:14:36.300 --> 00:14:38.820
And basically, what
we have to remember

00:14:38.820 --> 00:14:42.390
is that it is not so
much what happens to us,

00:14:42.390 --> 00:14:45.720
but it is what we do
about what happens

00:14:45.720 --> 00:14:48.270
to us that really matters.

00:14:48.270 --> 00:14:52.770
So I know a little
bit about that.

00:14:52.770 --> 00:14:56.340
I became interested
in positive psychology

00:14:56.340 --> 00:14:58.410
and changed to
this new profession

00:14:58.410 --> 00:15:03.120
because my previous job left me.

00:15:03.120 --> 00:15:06.420
So in such a circumstance--
at least some of you

00:15:06.420 --> 00:15:07.630
think it's funny.

00:15:07.630 --> 00:15:11.550
I didn't think it was very
funny when it happened, exactly.

00:15:11.550 --> 00:15:13.565
It's always a little--

00:15:13.565 --> 00:15:14.190
lots of things.

00:15:14.190 --> 00:15:16.530
Downsizing, and-- so
no, everything's fine,

00:15:16.530 --> 00:15:17.940
but it is a little humiliating.

00:15:17.940 --> 00:15:19.680
There's a lot of
stuff that happens

00:15:19.680 --> 00:15:20.860
at that particular time.

00:15:20.860 --> 00:15:23.280
But had it not
happened, I really

00:15:23.280 --> 00:15:27.780
don't know why or how I would
have gone back to study--

00:15:27.780 --> 00:15:29.610
had the time to have
simply gone back

00:15:29.610 --> 00:15:33.100
and studied positive psychology
for real, which is what I did.

00:15:33.100 --> 00:15:35.490
And I learned all
this material, and I

00:15:35.490 --> 00:15:37.510
thought it was so
easy to implement,

00:15:37.510 --> 00:15:40.020
and so interesting,
and so ongoing,

00:15:40.020 --> 00:15:42.060
because the research
is constantly ongoing,

00:15:42.060 --> 00:15:45.210
it's a very new science,
that I decided--

00:15:45.210 --> 00:15:47.449
so in France, things are
sort of well-organized

00:15:47.449 --> 00:15:48.240
when you get fired.

00:15:48.240 --> 00:15:49.350
You know about that.

00:15:49.350 --> 00:15:51.600
And I had a little
time on my hands.

00:15:51.600 --> 00:15:54.600
So what I decided to
do was try everything.

00:15:54.600 --> 00:15:55.800
So I tried everything.

00:15:55.800 --> 00:15:57.160
I learned meditation.

00:15:57.160 --> 00:15:59.430
You guys know about
meditation, right?

00:15:59.430 --> 00:16:01.507
You know that meditation
can be learned.

00:16:01.507 --> 00:16:03.090
You don't just sit
there and meditate.

00:16:03.090 --> 00:16:04.090
It's actually a skill.

00:16:04.090 --> 00:16:07.350
It's like the rest of the
things that we know how to do.

00:16:07.350 --> 00:16:10.230
I exercised more.

00:16:10.230 --> 00:16:13.150
To be honest, I
began exercising.

00:16:13.150 --> 00:16:15.300
And I did write letters
to people in my life,

00:16:15.300 --> 00:16:17.670
because when you do
write letters to people,

00:16:17.670 --> 00:16:18.840
you are happier.

00:16:18.840 --> 00:16:21.720
And then at the end of
this particular year--

00:16:21.720 --> 00:16:23.460
I have a tendency
to forget things.

00:16:23.460 --> 00:16:25.200
I didn't want to
forget this time.

00:16:25.200 --> 00:16:28.920
So I decided to sit down
and write the story.

00:16:28.920 --> 00:16:32.856
And when the book came
out here in France,

00:16:32.856 --> 00:16:34.230
the book did very
well instantly,

00:16:34.230 --> 00:16:35.220
so that was a surprise.

00:16:35.220 --> 00:16:36.840
But I realized
something very simple.

00:16:36.840 --> 00:16:40.500
That although we are very unique
individuals, there's something

00:16:40.500 --> 00:16:42.630
we have all in common.

00:16:42.630 --> 00:16:46.890
With more information,
we make better decisions.

00:16:46.890 --> 00:16:50.100
And the more we know
about behaviors, the freer

00:16:50.100 --> 00:16:53.010
we are to choose to
implement these behaviors

00:16:53.010 --> 00:16:54.150
or to try things out.

00:16:54.150 --> 00:16:57.420
And that's how I decided
to go on and keep talking

00:16:57.420 --> 00:17:02.260
about this particular topic.

00:17:02.260 --> 00:17:10.829
Then, as we say in French,
basically, [FRENCH]..

00:17:10.829 --> 00:17:14.099
Basically, a bus ran me over.

00:17:14.099 --> 00:17:15.150
Not literally.

00:17:15.150 --> 00:17:17.430
But we will all be
run over by buses.

00:17:17.430 --> 00:17:21.720
And in my case, what
happened is that I had

00:17:21.720 --> 00:17:24.119
a very close and dear cousin.

00:17:24.119 --> 00:17:26.700
His name was David
Servan-Schreiber.

00:17:26.700 --> 00:17:29.130
Some of you may know his name.

00:17:29.130 --> 00:17:31.230
And David was my age.

00:17:31.230 --> 00:17:32.980
And David died.

00:17:32.980 --> 00:17:34.260
He died from brain tumor.

00:17:34.260 --> 00:17:38.350
He was a doctor, and as a
doctor, when he was diagnosed,

00:17:38.350 --> 00:17:40.410
he was diagnosed when
he was 30 years old.

00:17:40.410 --> 00:17:44.250
And he decided to look for ways
that he could fight cancer.

00:17:44.250 --> 00:17:45.870
His doctors said,
just go on and live

00:17:45.870 --> 00:17:47.020
the way you live your life.

00:17:47.020 --> 00:17:48.520
And he said, no, I
don't believe that,

00:17:48.520 --> 00:17:50.686
and I'm sure there's something
better that I can do.

00:17:50.686 --> 00:17:54.990
So he began compulsing
all the research that

00:17:54.990 --> 00:17:57.600
has been done about
fighting cancer cells that

00:17:57.600 --> 00:18:00.710
weren't really promoted, and
basically completely changed

00:18:00.710 --> 00:18:05.240
his lifestyle and gained 20
years of life expectancy.

00:18:05.240 --> 00:18:08.970
Brain tumors usually win
the fight, and it did.

00:18:08.970 --> 00:18:13.440
David was a psychiatrist,
and he had built a training

00:18:13.440 --> 00:18:15.000
school for psychiatrists.

00:18:15.000 --> 00:18:17.310
And that company was orphaned.

00:18:17.310 --> 00:18:20.910
And one thing that I decided
to do one morning is I woke up,

00:18:20.910 --> 00:18:24.930
and I thought, OK, I'm going to
buy this company from his kids,

00:18:24.930 --> 00:18:27.240
and I'm going to
continue his work.

00:18:27.240 --> 00:18:31.110
And that's when all my
little voices woke up.

00:18:31.110 --> 00:18:34.410
So one little voice here
told me, Flo, let me just

00:18:34.410 --> 00:18:36.990
remind you, you can't count.

00:18:36.990 --> 00:18:39.060
Which is not untrue.

00:18:39.060 --> 00:18:42.090
And then another voice
here said, you did already

00:18:42.090 --> 00:18:43.430
start a company, remember?

00:18:43.430 --> 00:18:45.236
And the company went broke.

00:18:45.236 --> 00:18:46.860
Are you sure you want
to do that again?

00:18:46.860 --> 00:18:49.800
And I said, OK, girls, thank
you very much for the advice,

00:18:49.800 --> 00:18:50.880
but I'm going.

00:18:50.880 --> 00:18:52.290
I'm going to do this.

00:18:52.290 --> 00:18:55.650
And this was seven years ago.

00:18:55.650 --> 00:19:01.140
I have no other
word to define what

00:19:01.140 --> 00:19:02.850
has happened to
us professionally

00:19:02.850 --> 00:19:05.950
than to say that
we have flourished.

00:19:05.950 --> 00:19:07.200
You know what "flourished" is?

00:19:07.200 --> 00:19:08.610
[FRENCH]

00:19:08.610 --> 00:19:10.830
So how do you flourish
on a professional level?

00:19:10.830 --> 00:19:11.892
What does it mean?

00:19:11.892 --> 00:19:14.100
So it means, of course, that
all the jobs were saved,

00:19:14.100 --> 00:19:15.180
and we have created more.

00:19:15.180 --> 00:19:16.020
We've expanded.

00:19:16.020 --> 00:19:18.480
It means that we've gone
beyond our objectives.

00:19:18.480 --> 00:19:21.330
It means that we like
the way we contribute

00:19:21.330 --> 00:19:24.150
to the area that is ours.

00:19:24.150 --> 00:19:28.530
And it also means that we were
able to learn to work together.

00:19:28.530 --> 00:19:31.290
Because there were people that
I had not chosen, and they

00:19:31.290 --> 00:19:32.770
had not chosen me either.

00:19:32.770 --> 00:19:35.170
However, it did work out.

00:19:35.170 --> 00:19:38.290
So I began wondering,
how is it possible?

00:19:38.290 --> 00:19:42.300
How can somebody very normal
like me-- so I know two things.

00:19:42.300 --> 00:19:46.080
I was trained in English,
obviously, and in psychology.

00:19:46.080 --> 00:19:47.820
But running a company?

00:19:47.820 --> 00:19:49.260
Managing a team?

00:19:49.260 --> 00:19:52.560
Not only did I have no
appetite, but no intuition

00:19:52.560 --> 00:19:54.130
for that at all.

00:19:54.130 --> 00:19:55.480
But it worked.

00:19:55.480 --> 00:20:00.360
So that's when I began looking
at superpowers, obviously.

00:20:00.360 --> 00:20:05.010
And I started to wonder if there
weren't within each one of us

00:20:05.010 --> 00:20:07.920
very simple things
that we could actually

00:20:07.920 --> 00:20:13.140
count on when the storm started
coming up, and coming at us.

00:20:13.140 --> 00:20:15.150
So naturally, what did I do?

00:20:15.150 --> 00:20:17.430
I turned to positive psychology.

00:20:17.430 --> 00:20:20.250
And what this bunch
of researchers

00:20:20.250 --> 00:20:23.700
did when they actually began
positive psychology is they

00:20:23.700 --> 00:20:28.110
realized that there
was no universal list

00:20:28.110 --> 00:20:30.450
of human qualities.

00:20:30.450 --> 00:20:32.730
We did not know
what qualities were

00:20:32.730 --> 00:20:36.570
to be found across the world,
and that we could actually

00:20:36.570 --> 00:20:37.080
count on.

00:20:37.080 --> 00:20:39.060
So they began looking,
and they read everything

00:20:39.060 --> 00:20:41.280
that was published in
psychology, philosophy,

00:20:41.280 --> 00:20:43.590
religions, and put
them all together.

00:20:43.590 --> 00:20:49.050
And they came up with 24
common character strengths,

00:20:49.050 --> 00:20:49.960
they called them.

00:20:49.960 --> 00:20:52.750
Character strengths are
qualities, basically.

00:20:52.750 --> 00:20:54.990
And so they had to make sure.

00:20:54.990 --> 00:20:57.630
They had to verify that
these qualities actually

00:20:57.630 --> 00:21:00.600
really existed when you
went out to meet people.

00:21:00.600 --> 00:21:02.950
So they separated
in different teams,

00:21:02.950 --> 00:21:06.120
and my favorite
team went to Africa.

00:21:06.120 --> 00:21:09.420
And they go and visit
Maasai warriors.

00:21:09.420 --> 00:21:11.640
Now, Maasai warriors
are people who

00:21:11.640 --> 00:21:14.406
still hunt lions with pierces.

00:21:14.406 --> 00:21:15.780
"Pierce," is that
how you say it?

00:21:15.780 --> 00:21:16.140
AUDIENCE: Spears.

00:21:16.140 --> 00:21:16.740
FLORENCE
SERVAN-SCHREIBER: Spears.

00:21:16.740 --> 00:21:17.520
Spears.

00:21:17.520 --> 00:21:18.690
With a spear.

00:21:18.690 --> 00:21:21.420
And so they go to
the Maasai warrior.

00:21:21.420 --> 00:21:28.440
And they say, OK, this is for
a study that we are handling.

00:21:28.440 --> 00:21:34.390
Are you familiar with the
concept of leadership?

00:21:34.390 --> 00:21:37.320
So the Maasai warrior
says, yes, I am.

00:21:37.320 --> 00:21:38.430
Say, no, no, no.

00:21:38.430 --> 00:21:43.960
Do you personally know people
who actually are leaders?

00:21:43.960 --> 00:21:45.780
So the Maasai warrior
says, yes, I do.

00:21:45.780 --> 00:21:46.600
No, no, no.

00:21:46.600 --> 00:21:49.830
Do you know as many
men as women who

00:21:49.830 --> 00:21:52.180
actually express leadership?

00:21:52.180 --> 00:21:53.850
So the warrior says, yes, I do.

00:21:53.850 --> 00:21:55.920
Says, no, no, but
one more question.

00:21:55.920 --> 00:21:59.269
Would you like your children
to actually express leadership?

00:21:59.269 --> 00:22:01.935
And he said, of course I want my
children to express leadership.

00:22:01.935 --> 00:22:04.140
So they go, yeah, they
know about leadership.

00:22:04.140 --> 00:22:05.730
It's a familiar trait.

00:22:05.730 --> 00:22:07.980
And they did the same
thing with Eskimos.

00:22:07.980 --> 00:22:12.157
Eskimo [FRENCH].

00:22:12.157 --> 00:22:12.990
AUDIENCE: Fishermen.

00:22:12.990 --> 00:22:13.440
FLORENCE SERVAN-SCHREIBER:
Fishermen.

00:22:13.440 --> 00:22:14.800
Thank you very much.

00:22:14.800 --> 00:22:16.440
With Eskimos and so forth.

00:22:16.440 --> 00:22:19.590
And they validated
these qualities.

00:22:19.590 --> 00:22:22.840
So let's see what qualities
we have in this room.

00:22:22.840 --> 00:22:24.270
May as well.

00:22:24.270 --> 00:22:28.564
Who among you is funny?

00:22:28.564 --> 00:22:31.049
AUDIENCE: [CHUCKLING]

00:22:32.321 --> 00:22:33.570
FLORENCE SERVAN-SCHREIBER: OK.

00:22:33.570 --> 00:22:34.980
All right, that's not bad.

00:22:34.980 --> 00:22:38.790
You know, when you walk in
a class of elementary school

00:22:38.790 --> 00:22:43.240
children and you say,
OK, who is smart?

00:22:43.240 --> 00:22:45.360
Everybody raises their hands.

00:22:45.360 --> 00:22:46.440
So I'll ask it again.

00:22:46.440 --> 00:22:48.960
Who among you is funny?

00:22:48.960 --> 00:22:51.530
All right, OK, there you go.

00:22:51.530 --> 00:22:57.000
Who among you has
a sense of justice?

00:22:57.000 --> 00:22:57.990
Yes.

00:22:57.990 --> 00:22:59.400
Very nice.

00:22:59.400 --> 00:23:02.020
Who among you is perseverant?

00:23:04.590 --> 00:23:05.580
Yeah.

00:23:05.580 --> 00:23:06.480
OK.

00:23:06.480 --> 00:23:07.860
Wonderful.

00:23:07.860 --> 00:23:09.750
Little harder.

00:23:09.750 --> 00:23:12.614
Who among you is honest?

00:23:12.614 --> 00:23:14.290
AUDIENCE: [CHUCKLING]

00:23:14.290 --> 00:23:15.540
FLORENCE SERVAN-SCHREIBER: OK.

00:23:15.540 --> 00:23:18.090
Most of you are more
honest than you think.

00:23:18.090 --> 00:23:19.650
OK, let me just check.

00:23:19.650 --> 00:23:22.422
Who's ever kissed anyone?

00:23:22.422 --> 00:23:23.655
AUDIENCE: [CHUCKLING]

00:23:23.655 --> 00:23:26.030
FLORENCE SERVAN-SCHREIBER:
OK, this is a happiness class.

00:23:26.030 --> 00:23:28.830
There are things that are
worth living for, you know?

00:23:28.830 --> 00:23:30.650
Things that you
could actually try.

00:23:30.650 --> 00:23:35.090
So these are very
common qualities.

00:23:35.090 --> 00:23:37.220
And what is a superpower?

00:23:37.220 --> 00:23:43.310
It's a very common quality,
except that it's yours.

00:23:43.310 --> 00:23:45.570
So basically, how do you use it?

00:23:45.570 --> 00:23:48.740
So the culture that I
come from, being French,

00:23:48.740 --> 00:23:51.040
you have to know, if you're
not from this country,

00:23:51.040 --> 00:23:55.200
that talking about your
qualities just never happens.

00:23:55.200 --> 00:23:56.630
It's not something we do.

00:23:56.630 --> 00:23:57.770
It's rude.

00:23:57.770 --> 00:23:59.330
It's pretentious.

00:23:59.330 --> 00:24:01.580
It's absolutely not
something we ever do.

00:24:01.580 --> 00:24:03.800
So when we do come up
with a list like that,

00:24:03.800 --> 00:24:05.649
it's very useful,
because all of a sudden,

00:24:05.649 --> 00:24:07.190
there's something
a little objective.

00:24:07.190 --> 00:24:09.106
Because actually, what
you do is you go online

00:24:09.106 --> 00:24:10.770
and you answer a
bunch of questions.

00:24:10.770 --> 00:24:12.470
And at the end of
the questionnaire,

00:24:12.470 --> 00:24:14.270
you are given the
answers that tell you,

00:24:14.270 --> 00:24:18.090
OK, among the 24 universal
character strengths,

00:24:18.090 --> 00:24:20.090
this is how yours are organized.

00:24:20.090 --> 00:24:22.230
And then you know how it works.

00:24:22.230 --> 00:24:23.840
Why is it useful?

00:24:23.840 --> 00:24:25.350
I'll give you an example.

00:24:25.350 --> 00:24:29.270
When I decided to
write this book,

00:24:29.270 --> 00:24:31.370
I had no idea how
you write a book.

00:24:31.370 --> 00:24:34.280
So I actually went and
asked people, senior people

00:24:34.280 --> 00:24:35.510
who had written books.

00:24:35.510 --> 00:24:39.330
They all came up with the
different ways that they do it.

00:24:39.330 --> 00:24:42.290
But one thing came
back systematically.

00:24:42.290 --> 00:24:45.590
All of them told me,
you sit down at 8:00 AM,

00:24:45.590 --> 00:24:49.560
and you do not get
up until 12:00.

00:24:49.560 --> 00:24:53.030
So I sat down at 8:00 AM.

00:24:53.030 --> 00:24:54.711
And I had the
title of the book--

00:24:54.711 --> 00:24:55.460
"3 Kifs Par Jour."

00:24:55.460 --> 00:24:57.316
That I knew.

00:24:57.316 --> 00:24:57.816
Tsh.

00:25:03.490 --> 00:25:04.080
9 o'clock.

00:25:07.100 --> 00:25:08.870
I'm sitting down.

00:25:08.870 --> 00:25:09.585
10 o'clock.

00:25:15.810 --> 00:25:17.780
11 o'clock.

00:25:17.780 --> 00:25:19.250
Balance it out.

00:25:19.250 --> 00:25:20.610
11:30.

00:25:20.610 --> 00:25:21.770
12 o'clock.

00:25:21.770 --> 00:25:26.427
And by 12 o'clock, I feel like
a pile of dust under my desk.

00:25:26.427 --> 00:25:28.010
And I say to myself,
how do you expect

00:25:28.010 --> 00:25:31.550
to write a book considering you
can't even stay on your chair,

00:25:31.550 --> 00:25:32.780
basically?

00:25:32.780 --> 00:25:36.360
And I did tell you earlier, I
think that I forget everything.

00:25:36.360 --> 00:25:38.810
One thing that I had
forgotten when I actually

00:25:38.810 --> 00:25:40.940
studied positive
psychology-- of course

00:25:40.940 --> 00:25:42.190
I answered this questionnaire.

00:25:42.190 --> 00:25:45.030
It's one of the basic
things that you do.

00:25:45.030 --> 00:25:48.560
And there is a quality that
a lot of you here have.

00:25:48.560 --> 00:25:50.780
And you have to
know that I'm very

00:25:50.780 --> 00:25:53.720
impressed by how many of
you have this quality, which

00:25:53.720 --> 00:25:55.910
is called perseverance.

00:25:55.910 --> 00:25:59.210
Perseverance is the ability
to start something and take it

00:25:59.210 --> 00:26:02.360
all the way until it's done.

00:26:02.360 --> 00:26:06.770
When I answer the questionnaire,
out of the 24 strengths,

00:26:06.770 --> 00:26:12.140
my 24th strength
is perseverance.

00:26:12.140 --> 00:26:15.770
Which means that, in
this life, I will never

00:26:15.770 --> 00:26:18.170
experience perseverance.

00:26:18.170 --> 00:26:20.875
And it absolutely
does not matter.

00:26:20.875 --> 00:26:22.250
And what we have
to understand is

00:26:22.250 --> 00:26:26.420
that, if we do want
to take on challenges,

00:26:26.420 --> 00:26:30.040
to have interesting
relationships with people,

00:26:30.040 --> 00:26:32.690
to be excited about the projects
that we're actually running,

00:26:32.690 --> 00:26:35.240
and enjoy doing
what we're doing,

00:26:35.240 --> 00:26:41.090
we have to honor the strengths
that come to us naturally.

00:26:41.090 --> 00:26:44.620
So in my case, I'll give
you my first top five.

00:26:44.620 --> 00:26:47.270
The number one is curiosity.

00:26:47.270 --> 00:26:49.670
Number two is creativity.

00:26:49.670 --> 00:26:54.020
Number three is the ability
to love, and be loved.

00:26:54.020 --> 00:26:57.260
Meaning that people
matter a lot to me.

00:26:57.260 --> 00:27:01.500
Number four, I did not even
know it was a strength.

00:27:01.500 --> 00:27:04.100
It's called
recognition of beauty.

00:27:04.100 --> 00:27:06.920
It means that I'm very
sensitive to beauty around me,

00:27:06.920 --> 00:27:10.050
but also to a job well done.

00:27:10.050 --> 00:27:13.690
And then number
four is called zest.

00:27:13.690 --> 00:27:15.740
Joie de vivre.

00:27:15.740 --> 00:27:18.320
How do you write a
book with these things?

00:27:18.320 --> 00:27:20.840
Basically, the way
it works is that I

00:27:20.840 --> 00:27:23.960
do sit down at 8 o'clock,
just like the perseverance.

00:27:23.960 --> 00:27:26.000
My brain is fresher, yes.

00:27:26.000 --> 00:27:28.560
But I do exactly what I can.

00:27:28.560 --> 00:27:30.742
And when I can't take
it anymore, I do get up

00:27:30.742 --> 00:27:32.450
and I go in the room
next door, and it so

00:27:32.450 --> 00:27:33.890
happens to be the kitchen.

00:27:33.890 --> 00:27:36.740
And with my fingers, my creative
fingers who cannot just do

00:27:36.740 --> 00:27:39.680
intellectual stuff, I will
either cook something or make

00:27:39.680 --> 00:27:40.550
myself a cup of tea.

00:27:40.550 --> 00:27:41.310
It doesn't matter.

00:27:41.310 --> 00:27:43.430
I need to use my
fingers differently.

00:27:43.430 --> 00:27:44.540
I come back.

00:27:44.540 --> 00:27:45.530
I sit down.

00:27:45.530 --> 00:27:47.450
And when I get stuck
again, I'll probably

00:27:47.450 --> 00:27:52.250
grab a pen and start
drawing a star or whatever,

00:27:52.250 --> 00:27:55.700
because I'm thinking already
about the cover of the book.

00:27:55.700 --> 00:27:59.570
And it matters to me as much
as what's inside the book.

00:27:59.570 --> 00:28:01.560
And then I get back to work.

00:28:01.560 --> 00:28:02.990
And I live in Paris.

00:28:02.990 --> 00:28:04.136
When I get stuck again--

00:28:04.136 --> 00:28:05.510
I even live in
this neighborhood.

00:28:05.510 --> 00:28:06.920
You may see me walking around.

00:28:06.920 --> 00:28:09.590
When I get stuck again,
what I do is I go outside.

00:28:09.590 --> 00:28:12.560
And I need to see, I need to
count buses, and [FRENCH],,

00:28:12.560 --> 00:28:15.950
and whatever there is,
because my curiosity needs

00:28:15.950 --> 00:28:19.340
to be fed every day.

00:28:19.340 --> 00:28:20.840
And on the way back,
I will probably

00:28:20.840 --> 00:28:23.420
call somebody, and
have a conversation

00:28:23.420 --> 00:28:24.840
with a live person.

00:28:24.840 --> 00:28:28.820
And once I understood that
and honored that, not only

00:28:28.820 --> 00:28:32.360
was I able to hand my book
in with the 24 hours ahead

00:28:32.360 --> 00:28:35.360
of time, but most
importantly, I began

00:28:35.360 --> 00:28:37.730
enjoying what I was doing.

00:28:37.730 --> 00:28:40.340
And what we each and every
one of us has to remember

00:28:40.340 --> 00:28:44.930
is that we are
completely unique.

00:28:44.930 --> 00:28:50.660
We are a completely unique
composition of these qualities.

00:28:50.660 --> 00:28:52.880
Statistically, it's
impossible to have somebody

00:28:52.880 --> 00:28:57.230
in this room who has the
same design of qualities

00:28:57.230 --> 00:28:58.760
than you have.

00:28:58.760 --> 00:29:03.960
And probably, if you are stuck
in anything in your life--

00:29:03.960 --> 00:29:06.500
whether it's a project that's
difficult, or communicating

00:29:06.500 --> 00:29:08.900
with your kids, communicating
with your lover, whatever

00:29:08.900 --> 00:29:10.190
it is--

00:29:10.190 --> 00:29:14.600
you are probably not
using your top qualities.

00:29:14.600 --> 00:29:17.120
And you are probably using the
ones that are in the middle,

00:29:17.120 --> 00:29:19.610
or maybe the worst
part is in the bottom.

00:29:19.610 --> 00:29:23.370
The French school system
is very perseverant.

00:29:23.370 --> 00:29:27.290
I was a very miserable
student in school.

00:29:27.290 --> 00:29:30.560
But now that I can design my
own line of work, and the way

00:29:30.560 --> 00:29:32.240
I do it, and however
I want to do it,

00:29:32.240 --> 00:29:36.410
of course there's practically
no limit to where you can go

00:29:36.410 --> 00:29:38.510
once you start respecting that.

00:29:38.510 --> 00:29:40.655
So when I was looking
for superpowers,

00:29:40.655 --> 00:29:42.280
I also began wondering
if there weren't

00:29:42.280 --> 00:29:44.405
things that were a little
more common to everybody,

00:29:44.405 --> 00:29:47.250
not as singular as the
character strengths.

00:29:47.250 --> 00:29:50.780
And I ran into something very
interesting called the others.

00:29:50.780 --> 00:29:52.296
Other people.

00:29:52.296 --> 00:29:54.170
I don't know if you've
heard the fact that we

00:29:54.170 --> 00:29:56.840
are social creatures,
meaning that we

00:29:56.840 --> 00:29:59.300
are very interdependent.

00:29:59.300 --> 00:30:04.250
So if people look at
you with admiration,

00:30:04.250 --> 00:30:06.830
you will feel admirable.

00:30:06.830 --> 00:30:08.330
You say that?

00:30:08.330 --> 00:30:11.540
If people look at
you with criticism,

00:30:11.540 --> 00:30:13.790
you're actually going to
feel terrible about yourself.

00:30:13.790 --> 00:30:14.623
That's how it works.

00:30:14.623 --> 00:30:17.260
We are that sensitive
to other people.

00:30:17.260 --> 00:30:20.050
And there's one great study--
you probably heard about this

00:30:20.050 --> 00:30:21.250
study already--

00:30:21.250 --> 00:30:23.350
where researchers
come into classrooms

00:30:23.350 --> 00:30:25.960
where children are between
eight and nine years old.

00:30:25.960 --> 00:30:28.900
And they tell the teacher, we
came up with a questionnaire

00:30:28.900 --> 00:30:32.440
to determine if you have
high-potential students

00:30:32.440 --> 00:30:33.760
in your class.

00:30:33.760 --> 00:30:34.330
OK.

00:30:34.330 --> 00:30:37.270
So the kids answer
the questionnaires.

00:30:37.270 --> 00:30:42.500
They have no idea why they
are answering these questions.

00:30:42.500 --> 00:30:44.710
So they answer everything.

00:30:44.710 --> 00:30:48.130
Then the researchers
gather all the tests,

00:30:48.130 --> 00:30:50.470
and they thank everybody,
and they leave.

00:30:50.470 --> 00:30:53.560
They get to their lab, and
they throw everything out.

00:30:53.560 --> 00:30:56.350
They come back three
weeks later and say,

00:30:56.350 --> 00:30:58.840
we have looked through
every single test,

00:30:58.840 --> 00:31:00.645
which is completely untrue.

00:31:00.645 --> 00:31:02.020
We have looked
through the tests,

00:31:02.020 --> 00:31:04.090
and we have found some
high-potential students

00:31:04.090 --> 00:31:04.750
in your class.

00:31:04.750 --> 00:31:06.250
Would you like to
know who they are?

00:31:06.250 --> 00:31:08.170
Of course, the teacher says yes.

00:31:08.170 --> 00:31:10.120
They don't even go
and see the kids.

00:31:10.120 --> 00:31:11.830
They ask for a list.

00:31:11.830 --> 00:31:14.590
And randomly,
completely randomly,

00:31:14.590 --> 00:31:16.780
they point to three kids.

00:31:16.780 --> 00:31:19.600
She's one, she's one, he's one.

00:31:19.600 --> 00:31:22.300
Those kids, that
particular year,

00:31:22.300 --> 00:31:25.120
made tremendous
progress compared

00:31:25.120 --> 00:31:28.630
to their other classmates,
and later on went

00:31:28.630 --> 00:31:30.550
for longer studies.

00:31:30.550 --> 00:31:31.450
Why?

00:31:31.450 --> 00:31:34.900
Because for one year, somebody
looked at them thinking,

00:31:34.900 --> 00:31:37.150
you are a high-potential person.

00:31:39.790 --> 00:31:41.930
And I can hear you.

00:31:41.930 --> 00:31:44.350
So the first thing that comes
through your mind is, OK.

00:31:44.350 --> 00:31:46.300
People should have
looked at me differently.

00:31:46.300 --> 00:31:47.500
Right?

00:31:47.500 --> 00:31:49.480
That explains it all.

00:31:49.480 --> 00:31:50.810
OK.

00:31:50.810 --> 00:31:54.160
And if by any chance, you
have children of your own,

00:31:54.160 --> 00:31:56.230
you are completely panicked.

00:31:56.230 --> 00:31:58.690
It is still time.

00:31:58.690 --> 00:32:00.850
But the question that
I would rather ask you

00:32:00.850 --> 00:32:03.100
is, how do you look at people?

00:32:03.100 --> 00:32:04.600
Because I know how
the French people

00:32:04.600 --> 00:32:07.250
look at other French people.

00:32:07.250 --> 00:32:08.500
But how do you look at people?

00:32:08.500 --> 00:32:12.730
Do you look at people wondering,
woof, look at this guy.

00:32:12.730 --> 00:32:17.830
Or do you wonder, what are
this person's qualities?

00:32:17.830 --> 00:32:19.060
What are their superpowers?

00:32:19.060 --> 00:32:21.040
How do I work with
these superpowers?

00:32:21.040 --> 00:32:23.830
Because in an ideal
world, parents

00:32:23.830 --> 00:32:26.110
would look at their
children like this.

00:32:26.110 --> 00:32:29.110
Managers would look at
their employees like this.

00:32:29.110 --> 00:32:32.380
Teachers would look at
their students like this.

00:32:32.380 --> 00:32:35.080
But then there's real life.

00:32:35.080 --> 00:32:37.090
I can testify.

00:32:37.090 --> 00:32:42.280
When my oldest son, Arthur,
was 21, he came to me

00:32:42.280 --> 00:32:44.020
and he said, OK.

00:32:44.020 --> 00:32:46.520
Mom, I'm going to Australia.

00:32:46.520 --> 00:32:49.360
So I'm trained in
positive psychology.

00:32:49.360 --> 00:32:51.370
The whole deal.

00:32:51.370 --> 00:32:56.090
And what comes out of my mouth
is, don't even think about it.

00:32:56.090 --> 00:32:57.640
That's real life.

00:32:57.640 --> 00:33:00.250
So what we need to do
about this information--

00:33:00.250 --> 00:33:02.560
just remember that
here, what matters

00:33:02.560 --> 00:33:06.890
are the 40% that we
actually have control over.

00:33:06.890 --> 00:33:10.300
I have no control
over what you're

00:33:10.300 --> 00:33:12.250
right now thinking about me.

00:33:12.250 --> 00:33:13.510
None.

00:33:13.510 --> 00:33:15.080
And I never will.

00:33:15.080 --> 00:33:16.210
That, I cannot control.

00:33:16.210 --> 00:33:17.950
I have no influence on.

00:33:17.950 --> 00:33:19.900
But this is what
I have control on.

00:33:19.900 --> 00:33:24.940
I can decide who I talk
to, and about what.

00:33:24.940 --> 00:33:27.340
Meaning, when
Arthur comes to me,

00:33:27.340 --> 00:33:29.990
because his plan is
to go to Australia

00:33:29.990 --> 00:33:34.600
and I'm unable to encourage
him, then his mission

00:33:34.600 --> 00:33:38.650
is to go to somebody else who
sees him bigger than he is.

00:33:38.650 --> 00:33:41.440
We all have in our lives
people that we actually

00:33:41.440 --> 00:33:43.540
turn to when we want to
do something difficult

00:33:43.540 --> 00:33:46.150
and we say, OK, this
is what I want to do.

00:33:46.150 --> 00:33:50.199
And then some people
will say, yeah, you know?

00:33:50.199 --> 00:33:50.740
I don't know.

00:33:50.740 --> 00:33:54.910
"I just wouldn't want you to be
disappointed" type of reaction.

00:33:54.910 --> 00:33:57.295
You don't go back
to these people.

00:33:57.295 --> 00:33:59.920
And then there's another type of
person where you actually say,

00:33:59.920 --> 00:34:02.860
I do want to go to Australia,
who would say, yes, absolutely.

00:34:02.860 --> 00:34:05.270
You have to go to Australia.

00:34:05.270 --> 00:34:12.639
We must know, in our lives,
who sees us bigger than we are.

00:34:12.639 --> 00:34:14.920
We can organize
our support system.

00:34:14.920 --> 00:34:18.040
We can organize the mirror
that is actually held

00:34:18.040 --> 00:34:21.190
in front of us, because this
is how we'll push forward.

00:34:21.190 --> 00:34:26.830
So let me finish with 10
happiness tips, if you want.

00:34:26.830 --> 00:34:28.449
Scientifically proven, OK?

00:34:28.449 --> 00:34:29.770
All of them.

00:34:29.770 --> 00:34:31.090
Number one.

00:34:31.090 --> 00:34:33.040
Savor more.

00:34:33.040 --> 00:34:34.600
[FRENCH]

00:34:34.600 --> 00:34:36.130
You know what savoring is?

00:34:36.130 --> 00:34:38.650
We spend so much time being
already in the "whatever's

00:34:38.650 --> 00:34:41.570
coming next," or still
in what came before,

00:34:41.570 --> 00:34:44.170
that most of the time, we
just forget to be here,

00:34:44.170 --> 00:34:46.310
doing what we're
doing right now.

00:34:46.310 --> 00:34:48.670
So one way to
savor is very easy.

00:34:48.670 --> 00:34:51.639
When we are actually somewhere
and happy about where we are,

00:34:51.639 --> 00:34:55.630
we turn to the person next to us
and we just say, this is great.

00:34:55.630 --> 00:34:58.120
That's savoring.

00:34:58.120 --> 00:35:00.600
Number two.

00:35:00.600 --> 00:35:06.430
Stop comparing
yourselves to others.

00:35:06.430 --> 00:35:10.150
Not only are you
fine the way you are,

00:35:10.150 --> 00:35:14.260
but it is the way you are
that we need you to be.

00:35:14.260 --> 00:35:16.450
Because that is when
you are the most

00:35:16.450 --> 00:35:21.670
singular, the most attractive,
the most competent,

00:35:21.670 --> 00:35:23.710
the most unique.

00:35:23.710 --> 00:35:27.700
There is absolutely nobody
else out there like you.

00:35:27.700 --> 00:35:31.820
And your only job is to live
with this particular person.

00:35:31.820 --> 00:35:33.940
So that's all you have to do.

00:35:33.940 --> 00:35:36.550
And when I say stop comparing
yourselves to others,

00:35:36.550 --> 00:35:39.790
we usually compare
ourselves socially.

00:35:39.790 --> 00:35:43.930
So when it comes to happiness--
this is the next tip--

00:35:43.930 --> 00:35:47.170
think less about money.

00:35:47.170 --> 00:35:49.210
All the economists have
looked at the situation.

00:35:49.210 --> 00:35:54.980
What is the link between
wealth and happiness?

00:35:54.980 --> 00:35:58.660
So of course, if
you are destitute--

00:35:58.660 --> 00:36:01.210
if you are a refugee,
for example--

00:36:01.210 --> 00:36:05.020
it will make a lot of
difference, necessarily.

00:36:05.020 --> 00:36:07.600
But in this
particular room right

00:36:07.600 --> 00:36:11.110
here, it probably will
not make a difference.

00:36:11.110 --> 00:36:16.550
Accumulating goods has
never made anybody happy.

00:36:16.550 --> 00:36:19.790
There is one exception.

00:36:19.790 --> 00:36:20.520
Shoes.

00:36:20.520 --> 00:36:22.985
AUDIENCE: [CHUCKLING]

00:36:25.142 --> 00:36:26.642
FLORENCE SERVAN-SCHREIBER:
Next tip.

00:36:26.642 --> 00:36:27.526
AUDIENCE: Scientifically proven?

00:36:27.526 --> 00:36:28.480
FLORENCE SERVAN-SCHREIBER:
Scientifically proven,

00:36:28.480 --> 00:36:29.470
the shoes.

00:36:29.470 --> 00:36:31.294
And we're waiting for
the handbag research.

00:36:31.294 --> 00:36:31.960
It's on its way.

00:36:31.960 --> 00:36:34.295
AUDIENCE: [CHUCKLING]

00:36:35.200 --> 00:36:36.700
FLORENCE SERVAN-SCHREIBER:
Next tip.

00:36:36.700 --> 00:36:39.350
There are three
components to happiness.

00:36:39.350 --> 00:36:43.180
One is pleasure, number
two is engagement,

00:36:43.180 --> 00:36:45.610
and number three is meaning.

00:36:45.610 --> 00:36:47.920
Which means that
we need all three.

00:36:47.920 --> 00:36:49.300
Pleasure is not enough.

00:36:49.300 --> 00:36:50.500
Pleasure is great.

00:36:50.500 --> 00:36:52.980
Engagement means we
need to be part of.

00:36:52.980 --> 00:36:55.390
Parts of groups,
part of projects.

00:36:55.390 --> 00:36:57.550
There's something very
active about being happy.

00:36:57.550 --> 00:36:59.080
It's not just watching nature.

00:36:59.080 --> 00:37:01.360
Watching nature is
part of happiness,

00:37:01.360 --> 00:37:03.680
but there's something
very productive.

00:37:03.680 --> 00:37:05.330
But it's not enough.

00:37:05.330 --> 00:37:07.480
We also need to have meaning.

00:37:07.480 --> 00:37:10.000
Why am I doing all this?

00:37:10.000 --> 00:37:11.080
What does it bring to me?

00:37:11.080 --> 00:37:12.520
What am I bringing to the world?

00:37:12.520 --> 00:37:13.550
That's very important.

00:37:13.550 --> 00:37:14.994
So there too.

00:37:14.994 --> 00:37:16.660
If you think your
life these days is not

00:37:16.660 --> 00:37:20.260
exactly how you want it to be,
do you have enough pleasure?

00:37:20.260 --> 00:37:22.970
Sometimes we're changing the
world and we're super busy.

00:37:22.970 --> 00:37:24.820
But is it pleasant
enough for us?

00:37:24.820 --> 00:37:27.940
And then sometimes, we're
partying like wild people,

00:37:27.940 --> 00:37:30.190
and we're completely engaged.

00:37:30.190 --> 00:37:32.230
But is there any meaning to us?

00:37:32.230 --> 00:37:34.510
So it's a way of
adding what you need,

00:37:34.510 --> 00:37:37.530
or just making sure
everything is there.

00:37:37.530 --> 00:37:42.400
Following tip has been
proven by Maria Montessori.

00:37:42.400 --> 00:37:43.460
She works with children.

00:37:43.460 --> 00:37:44.510
She worked with children.

00:37:44.510 --> 00:37:45.890
We're big children.

00:37:45.890 --> 00:37:51.410
We're never as happy as when we
have decided what we're doing.

00:37:51.410 --> 00:37:54.857
So the best thing to do is
to take initiatives and say,

00:37:54.857 --> 00:37:55.940
this is what I want to do.

00:37:55.940 --> 00:37:57.392
This is what I want to work on.

00:37:57.392 --> 00:37:58.600
This is what I want to watch.

00:37:58.600 --> 00:37:59.860
This is what I want to eat.

00:37:59.860 --> 00:38:02.900
The more we express
our needs and desires,

00:38:02.900 --> 00:38:05.780
the easier it is to get there.

00:38:05.780 --> 00:38:11.230
Number six, cherish
your families.

00:38:11.230 --> 00:38:12.880
Cherish your friends.

00:38:12.880 --> 00:38:14.740
Cherish your colleagues.

00:38:14.740 --> 00:38:15.590
Why do I say this?

00:38:15.590 --> 00:38:20.420
Because the longest happiness
study began in 1938.

00:38:20.420 --> 00:38:23.530
It was decided to follow
the entire class of Harvard

00:38:23.530 --> 00:38:24.220
University.

00:38:24.220 --> 00:38:26.200
All men at the time.

00:38:26.200 --> 00:38:29.380
And they all agreed to answer
a questionnaire every year

00:38:29.380 --> 00:38:35.110
about their life conditions
and their happiness levels.

00:38:35.110 --> 00:38:39.200
After 30 years, the
researcher retires.

00:38:39.200 --> 00:38:42.040
So the younger researchers come
in and say, so now, come on,

00:38:42.040 --> 00:38:44.350
you've been looking at these
people for 30 years now.

00:38:44.350 --> 00:38:46.330
Can you tell us anything
about happiness?

00:38:46.330 --> 00:38:49.510
Have you noticed any difference
between the ones that are happy

00:38:49.510 --> 00:38:50.815
and the ones that aren't?

00:38:50.815 --> 00:38:52.030
And he said, yeah.

00:38:52.030 --> 00:38:52.960
Absolutely.

00:38:52.960 --> 00:38:54.790
I know everything
about these guys.

00:38:54.790 --> 00:38:55.777
I know where they live.

00:38:55.777 --> 00:38:56.860
I know how much they make.

00:38:56.860 --> 00:38:59.350
I know if they are alcoholic,
if they're depressed.

00:38:59.350 --> 00:39:02.690
I know if their mother was nice
to them when they were kids.

00:39:02.690 --> 00:39:11.160
And the only thing
that matters is love.

00:39:11.160 --> 00:39:15.690
And when he says love, it's not
just romantic or family ties,

00:39:15.690 --> 00:39:18.060
but it is the nature
of relationships

00:39:18.060 --> 00:39:21.710
that we actually
have in our lives.

00:39:21.710 --> 00:39:24.540
Following tip, "trois kifs"--

00:39:24.540 --> 00:39:26.920
three good things.

00:39:26.920 --> 00:39:30.460
Count your blessings.

00:39:30.460 --> 00:39:35.860
A blessing is something
that you have the urge

00:39:35.860 --> 00:39:38.590
to say thank you for.

00:39:38.590 --> 00:39:40.120
Usually, it's called gratitude.

00:39:40.120 --> 00:39:42.670
It usually starts with
pleasure, but pleasures just

00:39:42.670 --> 00:39:43.960
fly out the door.

00:39:43.960 --> 00:39:47.980
Unless we stop just for a
second and think to ourselves,

00:39:47.980 --> 00:39:50.290
for that, thank you.

00:39:50.290 --> 00:39:54.160
When we do that, we can
gain up to seven years

00:39:54.160 --> 00:39:56.650
of life expectancy.

00:39:56.650 --> 00:39:58.510
There is a
physiological response

00:39:58.510 --> 00:40:01.360
to gratitude that will
make us live longer

00:40:01.360 --> 00:40:03.220
and in better health.

00:40:03.220 --> 00:40:05.450
The following tip,
exercise more.

00:40:05.450 --> 00:40:06.430
I told you.

00:40:06.430 --> 00:40:09.040
And I'm just talking
about mood exercise.

00:40:09.040 --> 00:40:10.690
I'm not talking about
physical health.

00:40:10.690 --> 00:40:12.340
Just the brain health.

00:40:12.340 --> 00:40:17.550
We were not designed to order
sushi and ride escalators.

00:40:17.550 --> 00:40:19.210
That was just not the plan.

00:40:19.210 --> 00:40:22.240
So our bodies are
completely underused.

00:40:22.240 --> 00:40:25.060
We need to use the body in
order to irrigate the brain.

00:40:25.060 --> 00:40:28.750
So it's three times, 30
minutes of aerobic anything

00:40:28.750 --> 00:40:29.717
that you want to do.

00:40:29.717 --> 00:40:32.300
When you live in Paris, usually
you walk around, so it's good.

00:40:32.300 --> 00:40:35.200
You're there already.

00:40:35.200 --> 00:40:36.700
Next before last.

00:40:36.700 --> 00:40:41.740
When you talk about
happiness, giving is always

00:40:41.740 --> 00:40:44.500
superior to receiving.

00:40:44.500 --> 00:40:48.140
Which means that every time we
do something for somebody else,

00:40:48.140 --> 00:40:50.050
we get a little
shower of dopamine

00:40:50.050 --> 00:40:54.080
up in the brain that makes
us feel absolutely wonderful.

00:40:54.080 --> 00:40:55.900
And then the last tip--

00:40:55.900 --> 00:40:57.910
this one is physiological.

00:40:57.910 --> 00:41:01.630
This one will work with
anybody, whomever you are.

00:41:01.630 --> 00:41:05.380
When you need to feel
better, right in a moment,

00:41:05.380 --> 00:41:08.830
in an instant, there's
only one thing to do.

00:41:08.830 --> 00:41:11.160
Smile.

00:41:11.160 --> 00:41:14.430
And when I say smile,
it's not smile.

00:41:14.430 --> 00:41:17.490
But when all the muscles
in the face are engaged,

00:41:17.490 --> 00:41:20.790
it's impossible to
experience dark thoughts.

