00:46:20.110 --> 00:46:22.410
But yes, it does
it does come from--

00:46:22.410 --> 00:46:25.420
the thing about positive
psychology-- and you know that.

00:46:25.420 --> 00:46:26.770
You all know that.

00:46:26.770 --> 00:46:30.345
When life is all right,
we need none of this.

00:46:30.345 --> 00:46:31.720
We need none of
this information.

00:46:31.720 --> 00:46:34.600
We just go on leading our lives.

00:46:34.600 --> 00:46:36.020
That's what we do.

00:46:36.020 --> 00:46:39.520
But when all of a sudden,
things get a little darker,

00:46:39.520 --> 00:46:41.680
and things get a little
more complicated,

00:46:41.680 --> 00:46:46.150
then it's very useful to know
that we have these resources.

00:46:46.150 --> 00:46:47.530
I'll give you an example.

00:46:47.530 --> 00:46:50.200
When it comes to gratitude--
my favorite absolute topic

00:46:50.200 --> 00:46:51.760
is gratitude.

00:46:51.760 --> 00:46:54.670
When the researchers
decided to look

00:46:54.670 --> 00:46:58.510
at what the impact of gratitude
can be, one thing they did--

00:46:58.510 --> 00:47:00.040
they actually found out.

00:47:00.040 --> 00:47:04.060
They decided to go, and
five years after 9/11,

00:47:04.060 --> 00:47:07.750
go meet with the
victims' families.

00:47:07.750 --> 00:47:11.620
They wanted to understand
what people had done

00:47:11.620 --> 00:47:12.980
in order to get back into life.

00:47:12.980 --> 00:47:15.040
How did they get back into life?

00:47:15.040 --> 00:47:16.900
And they found
different families.

00:47:16.900 --> 00:47:18.340
Some were not back into life.

00:47:18.340 --> 00:47:19.820
Some were already
back into life.

00:47:19.820 --> 00:47:23.080
And one of the differences
between the two

00:47:23.080 --> 00:47:25.720
is that the ones who
were back in motion

00:47:25.720 --> 00:47:30.730
were people who, before
9/11, in their everyday life,

00:47:30.730 --> 00:47:35.290
were expressing gratitude,
and feeling gratitude.

00:47:35.290 --> 00:47:39.040
So this is why, when we talk
about preventive psychology,

00:47:39.040 --> 00:47:42.670
the more in our
everyday OK lives

00:47:42.670 --> 00:47:46.150
we can practice to use
gratitude, for example,

00:47:46.150 --> 00:47:50.890
and to feel grateful, when
the storm hits the fan,

00:47:50.890 --> 00:47:52.720
we will have more training.

00:47:52.720 --> 00:47:55.944
It will be easier for us to
actually press on the button.

00:47:55.944 --> 00:47:58.360
So this is what is so precious
about all this information.

00:47:58.360 --> 00:48:02.470
Once again, it's just to train.

00:48:02.470 --> 00:48:08.350
The default mode of our brain
is to first perceive negativity.

00:48:08.350 --> 00:48:12.220
Whatever is wrong,
smells awful, is scary,

00:48:12.220 --> 00:48:17.410
has much more impact on us
than what is nice, and good,

00:48:17.410 --> 00:48:18.840
because we consider it regular.

00:48:18.840 --> 00:48:19.820
It's a safety measure.

00:48:19.820 --> 00:48:22.300
It's very useful for danger.

00:48:22.300 --> 00:48:25.900
But, however, for the day
we really get in trouble,

00:48:25.900 --> 00:48:28.870
it is definitely worth,
while things are OK,

00:48:28.870 --> 00:48:31.430
to start training with all
those little exercises.

00:48:31.430 --> 00:48:34.420
And optimism is one
that I really work on.

00:48:34.420 --> 00:48:36.160
I work on it.

00:48:36.160 --> 00:48:37.960
It's like an exercise that I do.

00:48:37.960 --> 00:48:40.300
It's like a physical exercise
that I do on my brain,

00:48:40.300 --> 00:48:43.381
or else I just think
the world is over.

00:48:43.381 --> 00:48:45.130
And every time one of
my kids had a fever,

00:48:45.130 --> 00:48:47.080
I thought he was going to die.

00:48:47.080 --> 00:48:49.780
So this is why we need to train.

00:48:49.780 --> 00:48:51.852
We all know what our levels are.

00:48:51.852 --> 00:48:53.060
We know what our buttons are.

00:48:53.060 --> 00:48:54.644
We know what our fears are.

00:48:54.644 --> 00:48:55.810
And we can help those fears.

00:48:55.810 --> 00:48:56.685
That's the good news.

