FLORENCE SERVAN-SCHREIBER:
Have people thrown it?

00:49:05.460 --> 00:49:05.960
Op!

00:49:05.960 --> 00:49:06.570
Woo!

00:49:06.570 --> 00:49:07.070
OK.

00:49:07.070 --> 00:49:09.070
SPEAKER 2: That's
throwing it, yeah.

00:49:09.070 --> 00:49:09.986
AUDIENCE: Here you go.

00:49:09.986 --> 00:49:11.622
AUDIENCE: Merci.

00:49:11.622 --> 00:49:13.080
I like it very much
when you shared

00:49:13.080 --> 00:49:14.830
the story of your son
coming to you saying

00:49:14.830 --> 00:49:19.590
he was going to Australia and
you were not really supportive.

00:49:19.590 --> 00:49:22.950
But what happens when you
actually try to be supportive

00:49:22.950 --> 00:49:25.290
but just think that someone
has a very bad idea?

00:49:25.290 --> 00:49:26.840
How do you manage that?

00:49:26.840 --> 00:49:29.550
Can I just say, go to someone
who is going to be supportive,

00:49:29.550 --> 00:49:31.500
because you really,
truly, sincerely

00:49:31.500 --> 00:49:33.869
think that it's not a
good thing for them.

00:49:33.869 --> 00:49:35.660
FLORENCE SERVAN-SCHREIBER:
Well, of course.

00:49:35.660 --> 00:49:37.750
That's called a debate.

00:49:37.750 --> 00:49:39.590
And you can get
into a conversation.

00:49:39.590 --> 00:49:41.010
In that case, it
was a good idea,

00:49:41.010 --> 00:49:43.050
so I had nothing more to say.

00:49:43.050 --> 00:49:45.780
But of course, you debate
your ideas, necessarily.

00:49:45.780 --> 00:49:47.725
And people do have
terrible ideas.

00:49:47.725 --> 00:49:49.350
And when you're a
mother, wait till you

00:49:49.350 --> 00:49:51.044
see what ideas your kids have.

00:49:51.044 --> 00:49:52.085
They have terrible ideas.

00:49:52.085 --> 00:49:53.251
AUDIENCE: I can see already.

00:49:56.930 --> 00:49:58.980
AUDIENCE: I just wanted
to ask you a question.

00:49:58.980 --> 00:50:03.069
So if you do some readings,
or if you go to such talks,

00:50:03.069 --> 00:50:04.610
and you feel really
inspired, but you

00:50:04.610 --> 00:50:06.135
have someone that
you really love,

00:50:06.135 --> 00:50:08.510
and you see that they're stuck,
and they're in an unhappy

00:50:08.510 --> 00:50:11.150
place, what can
you do to help them

00:50:11.150 --> 00:50:13.400
without coaching them
or sounding like you're

00:50:13.400 --> 00:50:14.650
giving them instructions?

00:50:14.650 --> 00:50:16.400
I would be really interested.

00:50:16.400 --> 00:50:19.340
FLORENCE SERVAN-SCHREIBER:
That's a real life situation.

00:50:19.340 --> 00:50:21.920
We cannot change other people.

00:50:21.920 --> 00:50:26.160
That's the first thing we
have to admit and agree to.

00:50:26.160 --> 00:50:27.410
We cannot change other people.

00:50:27.410 --> 00:50:31.340
The only thing we can do
is do what we believe in.

00:50:31.340 --> 00:50:33.040
Because if you start
coaching somebody,

00:50:33.040 --> 00:50:35.600
they will maybe resist it.

00:50:35.600 --> 00:50:38.120
The only thing you can
do, if you strongly

00:50:38.120 --> 00:50:39.740
believe in being
a different way,

00:50:39.740 --> 00:50:41.390
is to actually be that way.

00:50:41.390 --> 00:50:44.870
And there's something that ends
up being contagious, or not.

00:50:44.870 --> 00:50:46.452
Not everybody will follow you.

00:50:46.452 --> 00:50:48.410
But at least that's the
only thing you can try.

00:50:48.410 --> 00:50:50.140
But going to somebody saying--

00:50:50.140 --> 00:50:52.550
a lot of people come to
my talks and say, ugh.

00:50:52.550 --> 00:50:54.300
I have to tell my
mother-in-law about you,

00:50:54.300 --> 00:50:56.120
because she really
needs your talk.

00:50:56.120 --> 00:50:58.520
That type of thing
doesn't really happen.

00:50:58.520 --> 00:51:00.770
The mother-in-law will
not make progress,

00:51:00.770 --> 00:51:03.350
because it's not her motivation.

00:51:03.350 --> 00:51:04.790
We do care for others.

00:51:04.790 --> 00:51:08.240
We would like them
to be more positive.

00:51:08.240 --> 00:51:11.480
But you also have to
understand something, is that--

00:51:11.480 --> 00:51:12.680
I have an aunt like that.

00:51:12.680 --> 00:51:16.910
She adores terrible news,
but adores to a point

00:51:16.910 --> 00:51:20.090
that it's insane.

00:51:20.090 --> 00:51:22.580
We have to respect that too.

00:51:22.580 --> 00:51:26.810
Some people feed on atrocities.

00:51:26.810 --> 00:51:28.520
And it actually does--

00:51:28.520 --> 00:51:30.920
it gives more energy
to their lives.

00:51:30.920 --> 00:51:32.420
So I will never change her.

00:51:32.420 --> 00:51:35.690
The only thing I can do, if I'm
around her, is just be the way

00:51:35.690 --> 00:51:39.560
I think that I want to be,
or that I think life can be.

00:51:39.560 --> 00:51:41.510
And sometimes miracles happen.

00:51:41.510 --> 00:51:42.950
People get better.

00:51:42.950 --> 00:51:44.300
And then that's another thing.

00:51:44.300 --> 00:51:46.130
Sometimes people need help.

00:51:46.130 --> 00:51:47.480
It depends.

00:51:47.480 --> 00:51:49.940
Sometimes people need
psychological help.

00:51:49.940 --> 00:51:52.610
And then we're not talking
about positive psychology,

00:51:52.610 --> 00:51:55.340
but this is a mental
health conference today.

00:51:55.340 --> 00:51:57.230
And mental health is a
whole different story.

00:51:57.230 --> 00:51:58.700
Sometimes, we
actually need help,

00:51:58.700 --> 00:52:01.775
and we have to be
able to get it.

00:52:01.775 --> 00:52:04.280
SPEAKER 2: OK, thank
you very much, Florence.

00:52:04.280 --> 00:52:04.730
FLORENCE SERVAN-SCHREIBER:
Thank you very much.

00:52:04.730 --> 00:52:05.410
SPEAKER 2: Thank you.

00:52:05.410 --> 00:52:06.951
FLORENCE SERVAN-SCHREIBER:
Take care.

00:52:06.951 --> 00:52:09.060
[APPLAUSE]

